In political science, delegative democracy is a system of government where elected officials are given nearly complete autonomy to make decisions on behalf of the people, without being held accountable for those decisions.
The characteristics of a delegative democracy are built on the principles of trust, autonomy, and individual responsibility.
The overall idea of delegative democracy as a system that promotes individual autonomy and decision-making.
Although delegative democracy focuses power on one individual, it can also lead to swift decision-making and efficient governance.
